{% extends "_base.html.jinja" %}

{# The CFD only uses the Period (window); the reference period drives
   aging thresholds + forecasts, not the CFD — so hide it here. #}
{% block filter_bar %}
  <nav class="filter-bar" aria-label="Filters">
    <div class="container">
      {% with hide_reference = True %}
        {% include "_partials/period_filter.html.jinja" %}
      {% endwith %}
    </div>
  </nav>
{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <style>
    .cfd-layout { display: flex; gap: 1.25rem; align-items: flex-start; margin-bottom: 1.4rem; }
    .cfd-chart-col { flex: 1; min-width: 0; }
    /* The chart tile's own margin would offset its border box inside the
       column while the panel stretches to the full row — making the panel
       taller top and bottom. Zero it so tile and panel align exactly. */
    .cfd-chart-col > .metric { margin: 0; }
    .cfd-panel {
      flex: 0 0 17rem; align-self: stretch;
      border: 0.0625rem solid var(--border); border-radius: 0.5rem;
      background: var(--surface); padding: 0.85rem 1rem;
      font-size: 0.8125rem;
    }
    .cfd-panel-hint { color: var(--muted); margin: 0; }
    .cfd-panel-date {
      font-family: var(--head-font); font-weight: 600;
      color: var(--p-600); margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    .cfd-panel-table { width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-bottom: 0.6rem; }
    .cfd-panel-table th {
      text-align: left; font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.05em; color: var(--muted);
      border-bottom: 0.0625rem solid var(--border); padding: 0.15rem 0;
    }
    .cfd-panel-table td { padding: 0.15rem 0; }
    .cfd-panel-table td:last-child { text-align: right; font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums; }
    .cfd-panel-flow { border-top: 0.0625rem dashed var(--border); padding-top: 0.3rem; }
    .cfd-panel-flow td:first-child { color: var(--muted); }
    @media (max-width: 56rem) {
      .cfd-layout { flex-direction: column; }
      .cfd-panel { flex: none; width: 100%; box-sizing: border-box; }
    }
  </style>

  {% with summary = {"title": "Cumulative Flow", "headline": cfd.headline} %}
    {% include "_partials/metric_summary.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  <div class="cfd-layout">
    <div class="cfd-chart-col">
      {% with mode = 'detail', data = cfd %}
        {% include "_partials/cfd_tile.html.jinja" %}
      {% endwith %}
    </div>
    <aside id="cfd-hover-panel" class="cfd-panel">
      <p class="cfd-panel-hint">Hover a day on the chart to see its flow
        metrics — items per stage, WIP, arrivals, departures, throughput
        and average cycle time.</p>
    </aside>
  </div>

  {% if cfd.daily %}
  <section class="ds-section" style="margin-top: 1.5rem;">
    <h2>Flow balance — daily arrivals vs departures</h2>
    <p class="filter-hint" style="margin: 0 0 0.5rem 0;">
      When the two lines track each other the system is balanced;
      arrivals persistently above departures means WIP is growing.
    </p>
    <div id="flow-balance-chart" class="metric-chart"></div>
    <script>
      (function () {
        const spec = {{ flow_balance(cfd) | safe }};
        function go() {
          vegaEmbed("#flow-balance-chart", window.applyTheme(spec), {
            actions: false, renderer: "svg"
          }).catch(function (err) {
            document.getElementById("flow-balance-chart").innerText =
              "Chart render failed: " + err;
          });
        }
        if (window.requestAnimationFrame) requestAnimationFrame(go);
        else go();
      })();
    </script>
  </section>
  {% endif %}

  <section class="detail-extras">
    <h2>How to read this</h2>
    <p>
      Each band is a stage. Its height on a given date is the
      count of items currently in that stage. Bands stack in
      workflow order top-to-bottom (entry stage at the top,
      terminal stage at the bottom); total stack height = items
      currently in the system.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Slope of the <em>top</em> = arrival rate. Slope of
        the <em>bottom</em> = throughput. Horizontal distance
        between them at any date ≈ lead time.</li>
      <li>A widening band for one stage = WIP piling up there,
        a likely bottleneck. A flattening band = work
        evaporating without progressing.</li>
      <li>Arrivals and departures tracking each other = balanced
        flow. The flow-balance chart below is the easier read
        for spotting the days WIP actually grew.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Possible next steps</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>If a single band stays consistently widest, set a
        <strong>WIP limit</strong> on that stage and review it
        weekly. WIP limits drive flow more reliably than
        adding capacity.</li>
      <li>Hover the flow-balance chart on a deficit run to find
        the exact date WIP started accumulating — that's where
        the operational change to investigate lives.</li>
      <li>If the top band is steepening (arrivals accelerating)
        while the bottom is flat: stop intake or split work
        before cycle time degrades.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <a class="back-link" href="{{ ("/workflows/" ~ contract.name ~ "/") | keep_filters }}">← Back to dashboard</a>
{% endblock %}
